59","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1180":"about 1180","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Topping","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","nickname from Middle English <i>topping(e)</i> ‘hair on the head’, probably given to someone with a distinctive head of hair or forelock. See also   Topp   and   Topham  .","perhaps from an unrecorded Old English personal name <i>Topping</i>, a pet form of <i>Topp</i>. See also   Topp  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tappin","meanings":["English:","variant of   Topping  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Tapping</i>, from Old English <i>Tæpping</i>, a pet form of the <i>Tæppa</i> seen in placenames like <i>Taplow</i>. See also   Tapp  ."]},{"name":"Toppin","meanings":["English (Cumbria): variant of   Topping  ."]},{"name":"Topham","meanings":["English (mainly northern, especially Yorkshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>Toppan</i>, of uncertain meaning. The second element is perhaps Middle English <i>pan(ne)</i> ‘(crown of the) head’, while <i>Top-</i> could be derived from several different words. If from Middle English <i>toppen</i> ‘to shave (the head)’, then <i>Toppan</i> might have been a name for a barber who provided tonsures for the clergy. Alternatively, <i>Top-</i> might represent Middle English <i>tup</i>, <i>top(pe)</i> ‘ram, male sheep’, hence ‘ram-head’, or Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>tupe</i> ‘hair on the head, tuft of hair, forelock’, denoting someone with a distinctive head of hair.","variant of   Topping  ."]},{"name":"Topp","meanings":["English: nickname, perhaps from Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, <i>tope</i>, Old English <i>topp(a)</i> ‘hair on the head; tuft of hair’, for someone with distinctive hair. Compare   Topping  . Alternatively, from Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, <i>tope</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>toup</i>, side-forms of Middle English <i>tup(pe)</i> ‘ram, male sheep’. A third possibility is a relationship name from the Middle English personal name <i>Top(pe)</i>, <i>Tope</i>, perhaps representing an unrecorded Old English <i>Top(p)</i> or <i>Toppa</i>, of uncertain origin, or else (especially in east and northern England) Old Norse <i>Tōpi</i>, <i>Tupe</i>; see   Toop  .","German: from Low German <i>topp</i> ‘point, tree top’, hence a topographic name from the location of the dwelling; alternatively, a metonymic occupational name or nickname from the same word in the sense ‘braid’.","German: variant of   Dopp  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Topping was born about 1180, in Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Catherine Bolton."},"et":{"about 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1180":"noin 1180","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1180–":"environ 1180–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1180–Male":"1180–Décédé","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1180":"environ 1180","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Thomas Topping est né environ 1180, à Everwyck, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Catherine Bolton."},"de":{"about 1180–":"um 1180–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1180–Male":"1180–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1180":"um 1180","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yor